keywords = {Part Deviations, Part Deformations, Tolerancing, Ontology},
abstract = {Geometrical part deviations are observed on every manufactured component and in modern manufacturing processes, understanding and mitigating such geometrical part variations is crucial to ensuring the quality and functionality of manufactured and assembled parts. Simultaneously, recognizing and considering part deformation during operational usage also plays a critical role, exerting a profound impact on component performance, reliability, and safety throughout its operational lifecycle. Traditional approaches have often dealt with each of these two phenomena independently, leading to fragmented understanding and ineffective solutions. To bridge this gap, a novel ontology is proposed to address the intricate relationship between different types of part deviation during manufacturing processes, as well as the possibility of part deformations throughout operational usage, while emphasizing their significance in tolerance analysis. By integrating knowledge from various domains, including engineering design, manufacturing, and materials science, the ontology facilitates a comprehensive understanding of the factors influencing part deviations. Furthermore, the ontology considers the probabilities of part deformations during the operational life, encompassing factors such as loading conditions, environmental exposure, and thermal fluctuations. By leveraging this ontology, engineers and researchers can better predict, assess, and manage the effects of geometrical part variation on product performance, resulting in improved design robustness, manufacturing efficiency, and operational reliability.}
}
